<br>
In Greek mythology, Prometheus was the Titan who stole fire from the gods and gave it to humanity. Arthur C Clarke's early novel &quot;Prelude to space&quot; had a nuclear powered ram jet for the first stage of a moon mission. It too was called Prometheus. This week Nasa's Administrator Sean O'Keefe announced a new Prometheus. A bold new nuclear space propulsion initiative which will do for spaceflight what fire did for human society. <br>
<br>
Nuclear rocketry is not a new concept. It has a long and controversial history stretching all the way back to the early forties when top scientists first began contemplating nuclear powered rockets for space. Engineers were putting successful prototypes together as early as the fifties. Each successive test in the ROVER program was an improvement on it's predecessor. The last model test fired before the program was abruptly cancelled back in the seventies had the abbreviated name of NERVA. It's performance in that test is still double anything we have ever managed to achieve since with chemical boosters. Nasa officials believe we can now increase that record to triple what is possible with chemical rockets and even that estimate may in the long run prove a conservative one.<br>
<br>
If fund requests from Nasa to congress are met then Prometheus is going to be a dream come true for those who have long awaited bold new changes at Nasa. The enabling technologies that will now be investigated have huge potential. Potential unrecognised to date simply because fear of it's side effects in the form of radiation have stymied all progress in the past. Nuclear power is still in its infancy as a result and only beginning to emerge from the trial by fire that all technologies must pass on their way to public acceptance. Recent surveys indicate that opposition to commercial use of nuclear power is diminishing and now stands at roughly 50:50 in the US. In Canada support actually outweighs opposition for new plants and this trend seems to be spreading in other countries. Thanks partly to the new agreements for reduction of greenhouse gases. Support for nuclear derived electrical energy is a promising sign for other peaceful applications such as space exploration where the fissionable elements at the centre of the controversy won't even be on Earth. Nuclear reactions are one million times more powerful than chemical and the developmental limitations for spaceflight applications with such a compact source of energy are impossible to predict. Faster, longer burns for deep space journeys would vastly increase mission parameters. Assistance to launch phases could eventuate in single stage rockets going from Earth to orbit and far cheaper payloads. The media has gone into a frenzy speculating about the future possibilities which include a &quot;Mission to Mars&quot; and &quot;Airline like access to Space&quot;. Even the British BBC has jumped onto the excitement bandwagon. A couple of websites such as Space.com and Spacedaily.com have expressed doubts about the veracity of claims that a Mars Mission might actually be on the cards, but nothing has dampened the growing public interest. <br>
<br>
How will other nations react to this startlingly bold new objective? The nuclear initiative was first announced over a year ago when Nasa requested a billion dollar funding over 5 years for nuclear space R&amp;D. There was little response to this overseas and nuclear power in the form of RTG's for space probes and satellites is nothing new. However, this latest announcement places nuclear power at the forefront of future space development. Spacefaring nations such as the European Space Agency and Russia cannot ignore this challenge. In particular the newest most ambitious kid on the block, China, will be watching how events unfurl very closely. In just over 3 years China has gone from no space capability to a planned human spaceflight in October of this year. A remarkable achievement spurred on by the realisation that the strategic importance of space will become central to tomorrows world order. National security dictates that a space presence is a sign of strength. Huang Chunping,   commander-in-chief of the chinese Shenxhou space launch program has said, &quot;Just imagine, there are outer space facilities of another country at the place very, very high above your head, and so others clearly see what you are doing, and what you are feeling. That's why we also need to develop space technology.&quot; <br>
<br>
Clearly the Chinese have more on their minds than national prestige in attempting to become the third nation to ever have launched a man into space. Manned aerospace is the epitome of space technology. While prestige is clearly an important consideration and one which westerners can easily relate to as they fondly reminisce about the moon landings, military impact is just as important if not greater a consideration. China has already invested too much money into space launch systems to consider pulling back now. They have big plans. In past interviews they have announced the intention to build space stations, reach the moon, build bases there and even boasted that they will beat the United States with a manned mission to Mars. Their Shenxou launch system has been played down by critics as primitive but is probably level with 1990's US technology and we are still using 1990's US technology. The five stage Saturn V boosters America once used for moonshots are now all gone and funding for Nasa's ailing programs such as the ISS have been diminishing annually. With Russia suffering economic problems and the ESA unsure of it's future China seemed to be on an inside straight to success. Prometheus changes everything. Nasa is &quot;moving from windpower to steam&quot; as Sean O'Keefe puts it and that may leave China suddenly out in the cold. Unless ofcourse they respond with their own nuclear space program.<br>
<br>
China and Russia have been increasing ties for a number of years now. Space and Weaponry technology trade in particular has increased with new treaties designed to smoothly assist such exchanges. Russia is no stranger to nuclear space technology with more experience in launching space reactors than the US. They had their own shadowy nuclear propulsion program which no doubt compared very favourably to past US efforts. If pushed to develop their own nuclear space initiative the Chinese will likely enquire of Russia for help. The Russians in turn will demand a high cost for such secret technology, just as they do for all space systems technology they have offered to China. Then China will either pay the fee or try to go it alone. China is no stranger to nuclear power and all nuclear facilities are state owned, just like the space programme. Efforts at combining nuclear and space branches of Government would face very little red tape within a communist regime and a chinese INSPI or Los Alamos seems very possible. The China Daily reports that 2.3 billion US dollars has so far been spent by China on putting a man into space and that's only the beginning of their ambitions. In October they plan to put a man into Space. On Monday, November 21, 1999 they launched their first unmanned space vehicle. The current Chinese space program started in 1956 with 30 young scientists and about 100 college graduates, some of whom didn't even know ``exactly what missiles were,'' according to a Chinese government publication. China invented the rocket almost 900 years ago and now they want to be at the forefront of modern development. A nuclear space race would see a return to the frenzied and visionary if politically induced days of Apollo. Let's keep our fingers crossed.<br>
